# Git Worktree Manager

## Script

The worktree manager script is at: `~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh`

Run it with: `bash ~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh <command> [args]`

## When to use

Use this skill when the user asks to:
- Create a worktree / start working on a new branch in isolation
- Switch between branches without losing work in progress
- Handle an urgent hotfix while a feature is in progress
- Move uncommitted code to a new branch (migrate)
- List or clean up worktrees

## Commands

```bash
# Create a new isolated worktree (copies .env*, symlinks vendor/)
bash ~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh create feat/ALM-1234/my-feature

# Create from a specific base branch
bash ~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh create fix/ALM-5678/hotfix main

# Migrate uncommitted changes from current dir to a new worktree
bash ~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh migrate feat/ALM-1234/my-feature

# List all worktrees
bash ~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh list

# Copy .env files to an existing worktree
bash ~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh copy-env feat/ALM-1234/my-feature

# Clean up finished worktrees
bash ~/.local/share/git-worktree/worktree-manager.sh cleanup
```

## Worktree location

Worktrees are created under `.worktrees/<branch>` in the repository root.

Example: `.worktrees/feat/ALM-1234/my-feature`

## After creating a worktree

Always tell the user to open the worktree path in a new terminal or IDE window:

```bash
cd .worktrees/feat/ALM-1234/my-feature
```

## Notes

- `vendor/` is symlinked, not copied — no need to run `composer install` again
- `.env*` files are copied automatically from the main repo
- Each worktree is fully independent: separate working directory, separate git index
- The same branch cannot be checked out in two worktrees simultaneously
- `.worktrees/` is automatically added to `.gitignore`
